{"author":{"id":"8e1777f58c0cfe5478428be8f9fcbfe90d25e44689578335da8fc2246fe0915a"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1452291013,"nonce":"vpFz6SiSxPSnPdIAqP8deV/STWQ=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDU6SXNzdWUxMjU3MDUxMDY=","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/522","origin":"github"},"title":"Project \"Conda migration\"","message":"As a few of you already know I have spend a few days to mass migrate TS packages to the conda build system. The aim was to simple deactivate the current TS dependency resolver and use the conda resolver instead ... a mid-term aim, I admit :)\n\nThe good news is that I was able to migrate a lot of our IUC packages in two days and uploaded them to [bioconda](https://github.com/bioconda/bioconda-recipes), a community maintained project (called conda channel). They are now alive and you can try them in Galaxy today :)\nI created a migration script from tool_dependencies.xml files to conda recipes based on @peterjc work. It is really messy because of so many exceptions and it does not work 100%. Nevertheless is saves a lot of time and generates nice recipes. It is actually fun to finally come up with tests and use them to test packages.\n\nHere it is: https://github.com/bgruening/planemo/tree/conda\n\nBasic packages like zlib, cairo etc. are already in conda, so less work and a really nice system to test dependencies as you probably all now, so this is a huge win.\n\nI encountered a few problems I want to discuss with you before I try to migrate the rest of IUC and devteam.\n## 1. namespaces\n\nWe have some wired package names, like `python_pillow` which should be `pillow` and is so in conda. But also some more subtle things like rnastar -\u003e star or vienna_rna -\u003e viennarna is a problem, Moreover, package names with dash ala `12-2013` are not allowed in conda.\n\nNamespace issue, but hey this was expected isn't it? The good part is that I guess 80% of all dependencies will just work if you switch your dependency resolver to conda. To get the other 20% working we need to find a solution. I see two possibilies:\nPlease let me know what you think\n- For recent tools change include a new \u003crequirement\u003e tag with the new name in addition to the old one. Galaxy will try as long as one name fits.\n- For old tools we can not do this any ideas here?\n- We could have a global galaxy namespace mapping file, for example `vienna_rna -\u003e viennarna`\n- We do not care as much as old tools needs to use the old backend.\n## 2. versioning and sustainability\n\nThe second and bigger problem is again about versioning, archiving and sustainability. As Galaxy project we have a strong commitment to reproducibility, this means archiving packages and keeping strict versioning. See our projects like [cargo-port](https://github.com/galaxyproject/cargo-port), [bioaRchive](https://bioarchive.galaxyproject.org) which is actually used by bioconda :)! or Galaxy own dependency resolver. In theory this is also easily possible in conda! Nevertheless as we all know this is hard and takes resources. \n\nFor example R2 versions are currently not available in conda. There are a few R3 versions in the main conda channel, but not all which we need. \nWe can create some, as done [here](https://github.com/bgruening/conda-recipes/tree/old_R) but it is unlikely to get them into the main channel. I had hoped that bioconda would be a possibility and I'm currently discussing this problem [here](https://github.com/bioconda/bioconda-recipes/pull/574).\nAs it stands bioconda wants to go with the most recent version and I'm sorry that I added so many older packages over the last days. It also seems that strict version dependency is not seen as necessary which kind of kills my effort to bring our packages 1to1 to bioconda.\n\nRead more here: https://github.com/bioconda/bioconda-recipes/pull/574\n\nSo what does this mean for us? \nDo we want to have a strict version dependency in the conda backend? Even in the case that this means that we need to have our own channel? Anaconda repositories are limited in space so we probably need to get in contact with them or we need to to find an other solution.\n\nI really had hoped to get our stuff in bioconda and join forces here, but with our focus on reproducibility it seems we are kind of isolated :(\n\nPlease let me know what you think and how you envision the future of package management in the Galaxy eco system.","files":null}]}